title: Prep Roundup: Local teams compete at Sharptop
text: Prep Roundup: Local teams compete at Sharptop by Tribune staff reports Cherokee Tribune October 21, 2015 01:00 AM | 483 views | 0 | 2 | | The River Ridge, Sequoyah and Woodstock cross country teams were in Jasper on Saturday for the Sharptop Invitational.Woodstock found the most success, with its boys team recording a second consecutive win with 49 points and its girls team placing fourth with 84 points.For the boys, the win came as a team effort, with all five qualifying runners finishing in the top 15. Corey Champion led the way, finishing fourth in 16 minutes, 46.85 seconds. Behind Champion was a pack of Kyle Pawlowski (ninth, 16:53.01), Austin Bailey (10th, 16:54.05) and Josiah Jaqua (11th, 16:54.62). Patrick Nolen finished 15th in 17:11.04.Brynne Sumner led the Lady Wolverines with a second-place finish in 19:19.86. Woodstock placed three more runners in the top 25, with Bailie McInnis 10th in 10:28.92, Hannah Everest 19th in 20:51.45 and Anna Baily 25th finishing in 21:02.44.Sequoyah also notched a pair of top-10 finishes. The boys finished fifth with 136 points, while the girls finished seventh with 233 points.Dalton Trampnau led the boys team with a 22nd-place finish of 17:29.91. Behind him were a pair of freshman in Aiden Heard (25th, 17:36.86) and Josh Meyers (26th, 17:37.41).Alyssa Cagle had the best finish for the Lady Chiefs, finishing 23rd in 20:59.85. Madison Stout (46th, 22:08.99) and Aleah Johnson (48th, 22:17.60) also recorded top-50 finishes. For River Ridge, the boys finished 12th with 351 points, led by top-60 finishers Jack Collins (59th, 18:17.63) and Chris Roeder (60th, 18:18.71). The girls team finished 13th with 363 points and was led by Vanessa Martinez (70th, 23:16.86) and December Wier (73rd, 23:29.41).Etowah was in Gainesville for the Coach Wood Invitational, with the girls finishing sixth of 19 teams with 190 points. Macki Walsh was Etowah’s top finisher, finishing 17th in 19:21.49. Madison Fowler (27th, 19:48.23) and Kyla Resnick (44th, 20:11.88) also ran well for the Lady Eagles.In the boys race, Etowah finished 11th with 309 points. Blake Beavers (24th, 16:39.57) and Nick Cooke (17:05.11) were the Eagles’ best runners.♦ ♦ ♦Cherokee County had a strong showing at the middle school state cross country meet Saturday in Cochran.Winning the race for the second consecutive year was Creekview junior program runner Nyah Hernandez, who ran the 2-mile course in 11 minutes, 57.05 seconds. Three other county runner finished in the top 10.Makena Gates, also of the Creekview program, was third in 12:15.66, and E.T. Booth’s Sydney Runyan came in fourth at 12:20.17. Dean Rusk’s Madison Ehmig rounded out the top 10, finishing in 13:00.39.E.T. Booth finished a county-best second in the team standings, with Dean Rusk eighth and Creekview 10th. In the boys race, Dean Rusk led the local contingent with a seventh-place finish, and Creekview finished 16th with 373 points. Alex Kendall led Dean Rusk, finishing 61st in 13:02.49, while Will Jobe’s 69th-place finish of 13:08.81 paced Creekview. Share This Article | similar stories
